******
[2] USA (California)
Date: Wed 9 Apr 2014
Source: KPBS [edited]
http://www.kpbs.org/news/2014/apr/09/san-diego-whooping-cough-cases-outpacing-2013-numb/


The rate of pertussis cases in San Diego County [California] continues to run far ahead of 2013, with 10 new diagnoses reported last week, the county Health and Human Services Agency announced on Wednesday [9 Apr 2014]. Nearly 200 cases of the disease that's also known as whooping cough have been logged so far in 2014, nearly halfway to the total for all of 2013, which was 430, according to the HHSA. By this time in 2013, 39 cases had been reported.

Two years after a KPBS/inewsource investigation posed serious questions about how well the whooping cough vaccine works, new research confirms the vaccine is failing at a higher rate than expected. "A greater number of children are getting sick with pertussis in 2014, said Dr Wilma Wooten, the county public health officer. "Parents or guardians should make sure their children have received all the recommended doses of the pertussis vaccine." She said it is also important that parents and other caregivers recognize symptoms immediately so that those sick with pertussis can get immediate treatment, and not spread the illness.

Infants younger than one year old are especially vulnerable because they do not have the full 5-dose series of pertussis vaccinations.

