[3] Canada (Alberta)
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2014
Source: CTV News [edited]
http://calgary.ctvnews.ca/whooping-cough-outbreak-could-be-larger-than-expected-1.1766513


Alberta Health Services [AHS] says 34 cases of whooping cough have been reported in southern Alberta since the beginning of 2014, and stress that there could be many more. One family in the community is urging parents to get their children immunized against pertussis after their 4 month old son became very sick.

A Lethbridge family is urging families in the community to get their children vaccinated after their son is very ill and under quarantine with whooping cough. The mother said, "Each [coughing fit] is really scary because it sounds like he's choking. It's day and night, so we take turns holding him through the night and switch off every attack." The infant ended up contracting whooping cough from his parents after his dad caught a very bad cough shortly after he was born.

The parents both had their pertussis vaccinations 9 years ago. They hope that their story can encourage other parents to get their children vaccinated. "Anyone who is pregnant or in that 5 to 10 year range needs to be getting it," the mother says. "Even if there's no outbreak. When you have an infant in the family, it's serious."

"Pertussis is really quite serious, especially in infants under the age of 6 months. This bacterium can intervene with their ability to breathe, and it can really lead to death," said Dr Judy MacDonald from the AHS.

The last outbreak in the South Zone was in 2012 and claimed the life of one infant.

[byline: Michael Franklin]

